- *1.* Compounds that contain a nitrogenous base, a pentose sugar, and a
  phosphate group are called (a) —————. Two purines found in DNA are (b)
  ———— and (c) —————. In DNA, the base pair (d) ———— is held together by
  three hydrogen bonds; the base pair (e) —— – —— has only two such bonds.
  When the solution containing DNA is heated, the optical absorbance at
  260 nm of the solution increases. This is because (f) ——————.

  *Answer:*

  a. *nucleotides* \
  b. *adenine* (A) \
  c. *guanine* (G) \
  d. *G–C* (or C–G) — three hydrogen bonds \
  e. *A–T* (or T–A) — two hydrogen bonds \
  f. *the double-stranded DNA denatures into single strands* (hyperchromic
  effect: unstacked bases absorb more UV light at $260 "nm"$).

#linebreak()

- *2. Indicate whether the following statements about DNA are true or false.*

  a. A-form and B-form DNA are right-handed helices, but Z-form DNA is a
  left-handed helix found only in single-stranded DNA. \
  b. Palindromic sequences can potentially form cruciform structures. \
  c. Deoxyribose is bound to the pyrimidine base at C-1'. \
  d. A pyrimidine in one strand of DNA always hydrogen bonds with a purine in
  the opposite strand. \
  e. G-C pairs share three glycosidic bonds. \
  f. All the monosaccharide units lack an –OH at C-2'. \
  g. The phosphodiester bonds that link adjacent nucleotides join the 3'
  hydroxyl of one nucleotide to the 5' hydroxyl of the next. \
  h. The two strands are aligned as parallel strands. \
  i. A-form DNA is shorter and has a larger diameter than the B-form DNA. \
  j. Nucleotide sequence has little or no effect on which form DNA takes.

  *Answer:*

  a. *FALSE.* Z-DNA is indeed left-handed, but it is *double-stranded*, not
  single-stranded. It forms preferentially in alternating purine–pyrimidine
  sequences (e.g., $"CG"$ repeats).

  b. *TRUE.* Palindromic sequences can fold back to form cruciform (hairpin)
  structures.

  c. *FALSE.* Deoxyribose is bound to the *nitrogenous base* at N-1
  (pyrimidine) or N-9 (purine) via an $N$-glycosidic bond, not at C-1'.

  d. *TRUE.* In Watson–Crick base pairing, a pyrimidine (C or T) always
  pairs with a purine (G or A).

  e. *FALSE.* G–C pairs share three *hydrogen bonds*, not glycosidic bonds.
  Glycosidic bonds link the base to the sugar.

  f. *TRUE.* In DNA, the sugar is $2'$ -deoxyribose, which lacks a hydroxyl
  group at the $2'$ carbon.

  g. *TRUE.* Adjacent nucleotides are linked by $3',5'$-phosphodiester bonds,
  joining the $3'$ hydroxyl to the $5'$ hydroxyl via a phosphate group.

  h. *FALSE.* The two strands of DNA are *antiparallel* (one runs $5'→3'$,
  the other $3'→5'$).

  i. *TRUE.* A-DNA is more compact (shorter axial rise per base pair) and
  has a wider diameter ($≈ 26 "Å"$) compared to B-DNA ($≈ 20 "Å"$).

  j. *FALSE.* The nucleotide sequence strongly influences DNA conformation;
  for example, alternating GC repeats favor the Z-form.

