- *3. Which of the following is true for DNA?*

  A. Phosphate groups project toward the middle of the double helix. \
  B. Deoxyribose units are connected by $3',5'$-phosphoanhydride bonds. \
  C. The $5'$ ends of both strands are at the same end of the double helix. \
  D. G-C pairs share three hydrogen bonds. \
  E. The ratio of A+T to G+C is constant for all naturally occurring DNA.

  *Answer:* D. G–C pairs share three hydrogen bonds (A is false:
  phosphates are on the outside backbone; B is false: they are
  $3',5'$-phosphodiester bonds; C is false: the strands are antiparallel,
  so $5'$ ends are at opposite ends; E is false: the A+T/G+C ratio varies
  between species).

#linebreak()

- *4. In the DNA sequencing by the Sanger (dideoxy) method:*

  A. The template strand of DNA is radioactive. \
  B. Enzymes are used to cut the DNA into small pieces, which are then
  separated by electrophoresis. \
  C. ddTTP is added to each of four reaction mixtures prior to synthesis of
  complementary strands. \
  D. The role of ddATP is to occasionally terminate synthesis of DNA where
  dT occurs in the template strand. \
  E. The sequence is read from the top of the gel downward.

  *Answer:* D. ddATP is complementary to dT in the template strand; its
  incorporation terminates chain elongation. A is false (labeled primers or
  ddNTPs are used, not the template). B is false (Sanger sequencing is
  synthesis-based, not fragmentation-based). C is false (each ddNTP is added
  to a separate reaction). E is false (the gel is read from the *bottom*
  upward — shortest fragments run fastest).

#linebreak()

- *5. The compound that consists of ribose linked by an N-glycosidic bond to
  N-9 of adenine is:*

  A. a purine nucleotide \
  B. a pyrimidine nucleotide \
  C. adenosine \
  D. AMP \
  E. Deoxyadenosine.

  *Answer:* C. Adenosine — ribose + adenine (no phosphate) forms the
  nucleoside adenosine. AMP would include a phosphate group (nucleotide).
  Deoxyadenosine would have deoxyribose.

#linebreak()

- *6. The phosphodiester bonds that link adjacent nucleotides in DNA:*

  A. are positively charged. \
  B. join the $3'$ hydroxyl of one nucleotide to the $5'$ phosphate group of
  the next. \
  C. always link A with T and C with G. \
  D. are positively charged and always link A with T and C with G. \
  E. are positively charged and join the $3'$ hydroxyl of one nucleotide to
  the $5'$ hydroxyl of the next.

  *Answer:* B. Phosphodiester bonds join the $3'$ hydroxyl to the $5'$
  phosphate of the adjacent nucleotide. The phosphate group carries a
  *negative* charge at physiological $"pH"$, making A, D, and E incorrect.
  C is false because base pairing (A=T, G≡C) is a property of the duplex,
  not of individual phosphodiester linkages.

