- *7. Nucleic acid samples have been isolated from three different organisms.
  The nucleic acids have the following base ratios (%):*

  #table(
    columns: 8,
    inset: 6pt,
    [ ], [A], [T], [U], [G], [C], [A+T/G+C], [A+G/C+T],
    [Sample 1], [20], [19], [0], [29], [30], [0.66], [1],
    [Sample 2], [24], [0], [16], [24], [36], [0.4], [1.3],
    [Sample 3], [17], [17], [0], [33], [33], [0.5], [1],
  )

  Which sample(s) are DNA? Which sample would you expect to have the highest
  $T_m$ (melting point)?

  A. 1 and 3; 3 \
  B. 1, 2 and 3; 3 \
  C. 1; 2 \
  D. 1 and 3; 1 \
  E. 2 and 3; 2

  *Answer:* A. DNA contains T (not U), so Samples 1 and 3 (containing T
  but no U) are DNA; Sample 2 (containing U but no T) is RNA. The melting
  temperature $T_m$ increases with G+C content. Sample 3 has $66\%$ G+C
  ($33+33$) — higher than Sample 1's $59\%$ ($29+30$) — so Sample 3 has the
  highest $T_m$.

